<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B62165378E8F89C263CF785" pageId="18" pageNumber="123" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B62165378E8F89C263CF785" blockId="18.[136,1452,1490,2092]" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B62165378E8F89C2585F8D1" bold="true" box="[189,735,1886,1912]" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Distribution, habitat and conservation status:</emphasis>
—Pantropical species according to 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6216537C3BF89C220BF8D0" author="Krapovickas, A." box="[1134,1361,1886,1913]" pageId="18" pageNumber="123" pagination="292 - 333" refId="ref19401" refString="Krapovickas, A. (2005) Malvaceae. In: Bacigalupo, N. M. (Ed.) Flora Ilustrada de Entre-Rios. 6 (4 b). Colecc. Ci. Inst. Nac. Tecnol. Agropecu, pp. 292 - 333." type="book chapter" year="2005">Krapovickas (2005)</bibRefCitation>
. Occurs in 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B62165378F1F8412657F834" box="[164,269,1923,1949]" name="Paraguay" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6216537940F84026DEF835" box="[277,388,1922,1948]" name="Argentina" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B62165379ECF84026A7F835" box="[441,509,1922,1948]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Brazil</collectingCountry>
according to 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6216537AC7F8402421F835" author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Morrone, O. &amp; Belgrano M. J." box="[658,891,1922,1948]" pageId="18" pageNumber="123" pagination="1 - 3348" refId="ref20813" refString="Zuloaga, F. O., Morrone, O. &amp; Belgrano M. J. (2008) Catalogo de las plantas vasculares del Cono Sur (Argentina, sur de Brasil, Chile, Paraguay y Uruguay). Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden 107: 1 - 3348." type="journal article" year="2008">
Zuloaga 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6216537AA1F8412471F835" box="[756,811,1922,1948]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">et al.</emphasis>
(2008)
</bibRefCitation>
and in 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6216537B9FF8402346F835" box="[970,1052,1922,1948]" name="Bolivia" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
according to 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6216537CE4F84022F2F835" author="Alverson, W. S. &amp; Michel, L. R. C. de &amp; Dorr, L. J. &amp; Fryxell, P. A. &amp; Krapovickas, A. &amp; Meneses, Q. R. I." box="[1201,1448,1922,1948]" pageId="18" pageNumber="123" pagination="786 - 819" refId="ref17710" refString="Alverson, W. S., Michel, L. R. C. de, Dorr, L. J., Fryxell, P. A., Krapovickas, A. &amp; Meneses, Q. R. I. (2014) Malvaceae. In: Jorgensen, P. M., Nee, M. H. &amp; Beck, S. G. (Eds.) Catalogo de las plantas vasculares de Bolivia, Monographs in systematic botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden. Missouri Botanical Garden Press., St. Louis, pp. 786 - 819." type="book chapter" year="2014">
Alverson 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6216537D48F841220EF835" box="[1309,1364,1922,1948]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
. In state of Rio Grande do Sul occurs in Coastal grassland, Shadow soil grasslands, 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B6216537C0BF86423E2F869" box="[1118,1208,1958,1984]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Aristida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="18" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Aristida</taxonomicName>
grassland, Araucaria Forest, Inland subtropical Forest, and in Coastal subtropical Forest (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B6216537B23F808248FF84D" box="[886,981,1994,2020]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="17.[136,229,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[267,1344,252,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-17@17.[205,1383,190,1929]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 8. Distribution map of Sida riedelii, S. ramoniana, S. regnellii, S. reitzii and S. tuberculata in Rio Grande do Sul state, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415505/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="123">Figure 8</figureCitation>
), in ruderal environments and anthropized grasslands. The species is here considered Least Concern (LC) because it has large EOO and AOO, since it is a frequent and ruderal species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
